GATX 20908, LOAD SULPHURIC ACID, WAS SPOTTED TO KLAMATH FALLS RIP TRACK FRO REPAIR OF BAD ORDER GRAB IRONS AT ABOUT 0130 8-4-92 BY SWITCH CREW. CAR WAS REMOVED FROM TRAIN 01-672-04 WHICH ORGINATES AT KLAMATH FALLS. CAR WAS RECEIVED IN INTERCHANGE FROM THE SOUTHERN PACIFIC RAILROAD AT 2347 ON 8-2-92. AT ABOUT 0730 ON 080492 MECHANICAL FORCES NOTICED SMALL PUDDLE OF LIQUID UNDER CAR WHEN THEY ARRIVED TO FIX THE GRAB IRONS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THROUGH EVALUATION OF SHIPPING PAPERS THAT THE TANK CAR WAS CARRYING SULPHURIC ACID.  INSPECTION OF CAR SHOWED SIGNS OF SPILLAGE OUT OF TOP OF CAR.  SMALL PUDDLE WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH BAKING SODA.  CHEMTREC WAS N OTIFIED, ALONG WITH NATIONAL RESPONSE CENTER.  SHIPPER WAS CONSULTED.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT A 100 LB RUPTURE DISC WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED. BURLINGTON NORTHERN MATERIAL AND PROPERLY-EQUIPPED PERSONNEL WERE USED TO ACCOMPLISH TASK.
LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE CAP LOOSE.  TIGHTENED CAP, NEUTRALIZED SPILLED ACID AND FORWARE\DED CAR TO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: THIS SMALL CARTON WAS REMOVED FROM THE DESIGNATED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL AREA ON THE DOCK AND PLACED ON THE TRAILER FLOOR, NEAR THE REAR OF THE TRAILER. THE DRIVER WAS LOADING HIS TRAILER, USING A FORKLIFT, AND FORGOT ABOUT THE CARTON, STRIKING IT WITH THE FIRKLIFT, CRUSHING THE CARTON AND RUPTURING THE CONTENT (METAL CONTAINER).  "ABSORBALL" WAS PLACED ON THE LIQUID THAT HAD DISBURSED FROM THE CONTAINER.  THE CARTON WAS THEN MOVED TO THE DOCK AREA WHERE IT REMAINED WHILE LAODING CONTINUED ON A FEW OTHER TRAILERS LOCATED AT THE DOCK.  GREAT LAKES TERMINAL (G.L.S. - SHIPPER) WAS CONTACTED.  THEY FAXED EMERGENCY CLEAN-UP PROCEDURES AND MSDS SHEETS TO OUR SAGINAW FACILITY.  "CHEMTREC" WAS THEN CALLED AND THEY ADVISED US TO CONTACT THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT.  BUENA VISTA TOWNSHIP FIRE DEPT. WAS THEN CALLED AND ADVISED US TO EVACUATE THE TERMINAL UNTIL THEY ARRIVED.  UPON ARRIVAL, THE ROAD WAS BLOCKED OFF, AND PEOPLE WHO WERE PRESENT DURING THE INCIDENT WERE WARNED THAT THEY SHOULD BE CHECKED OU BY A HOSPITAL/CLINIC TO MAKE SURE THERE WERE NO INJURIES.  AS OF THE INCIDENT DATE, ALL PEOPLE INVOLVED HAVE BEEN CHECKED OUT AND RELEASED.  AFTER THE ARRIVAL OF THE BUENA-VISTA FIRE DEPT., "BERLEINS ENVIRONMENTAL" AND "K & D INDUSTRIAL" WAS CONTACTED FOR CLEAN-UP, BUT REFUSED, DUE TO THE HAZ-MAT BEING A "LEVEL 1" PRIORITY, AND WOULD REQUIRE SPECIAL HANDLING.  IT WAS THEN RECOMMENDED THAT "YOUNGS ENVIRONMENTAL BE CONTACTED, WHICH WE DID.  WHEN YOUNG'S ENVIRONMENTAL ARRIVED, THEY CONTAINED THE SPILL, CLEANED UP ALL DIRT, DEBRIS, CLOTHING FROM A FEW OF OUR EMPLOYEES, AND ABSORBALL, AND PLACED IT ALL IN (8) EIGHT, (5) FIVE GALLON HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WASTE PAILS.  AS OF THIS DATE, 8/18/92, YOUNGS ENVIRONMENTAL IS WAITING FOR AUTHORITY FROM THE HAZARDOUS WASTE SITE TO TRANSPORT THE WASTE TO THEM.  THEREFORE, A HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST CANNOT BE SUPPLIED AT THIS TIME.

WHEN REACHING FACILITY, DRIVER DISCOVERED SPILLAGE. HE THEN DONNED HIS SAFETY - EQUIPMENT, RESPIRATOR,GOGGLES, AND GLOVES. BEGAN HIS CLEAN-UP OF SPILL WITH ABSORBENT (SAW-DUST) MATERIAL, AND STORED WITHIN PROPER CONTAINER. RECOMMENDATIONS WERE STATED TO LOCATION OF PICK-UP ABOUT BETTER STEPS IN INSPECTING BEFORE BEING ACCEPTED FOR TRANSPORTATION.
FITTING AT END OF DISCHARGE (PUMP) HOSE HAD A CRACK. WHEN PRODUCT WAS PUMPED A SPRAY OF KEROSENE HIT THE DRIVER, A SMALL AMOUNT AT THE GROUND.
WHILE TRANSFERRING PRODUCT FROM 1 TRAILER TO ANOTHER, PUMP WAS NOT SHUT OFF IN TIME AND PRODUCT SPILLED FROM TANK TOP.

THE SHIPPER LOADED 5 TOTE BINS ONTO CF'S TRAILER, WHILE ENROUTE TO THE LOACL TERMINAL, THE LID CAME LOOSE ON THE SECOND BIN FROM THE NOSE OF THE TRAILER ALLOWING APPROXIMATELY 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SLOSH OUT. WHEN THE DOCKMAN OPENED THE TRAILER DOOR, THE SPILL WAS REPORTED TO THE SUPERVISOR ON DUTY. THE SHIPPER COULD NOT BE REACHED UNTIL THE MORNING OF 08/11/92. THEY WERE CONTACTED AT 08:00 TO REPORT THE INCIDENT. THEIR SAFETY MANAGER AND ONE OTHER EMPLOYEE CAME TO THE TERMINAL TO INVESTIGATE THE INCIDENT. THEY REPLACED THE LID ON THE OPEN BIN AND ASKED US TO BRING THE TRAILER TO THEIR PLANT FOR CLEANUP. THEY ATTEMPTED TO IDENTIFY THE EMPLOYEE WHO CLOSED THE LID INITIALLY SO THEY COULD RETRAIN HIM.
WHEN LOADING THIS PAIL, A SMALL PIN HOLE WAS NOTICED. MATERIALIS ON DOCK WAITING FOR DISPOSITION FROM SHIPPER.

EGC CALLED AND ASKED FOR ME TO HANDLE INCIDENT IN NEW ORLEANS, L.A. I CONTACTED YARD AND WAS TOLD THAT CREW SMELLED STRONG ODOR COMING FROM CAR, BUT FOUND NO OBVIOUS LEAKING. I CONTACTED SHIPPER AND ALL AGREED TO SEND CONTRACTOR TO LOOK AT CAR. CONTRACTOR FOUND PRESSURE RELIEF VALVE NUTS LOOSE. THEY WERE TIGHTENED DOWN AND CAR WAS RELEASED.
CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE TOP WHEN MOVED. CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED. BORS INSPECTOR REPLACED BLOWN RUPTURE DISC. CAR WAS RELEASED AT 14:00.

TRAIN CREW WAS SORTING OUT GATX 22311 INTO RUETGERS NEASE WHEN CONDUCTOR HARRY DENHAM, WHO WAS STANDING NEXT TO CAR, WAS SPLASHED ON HAND,NECK AND SHIRT. HE QUICKLY RAN TO SHOWER INSIDE RUETGERS NEASE AND SHOWERED OFF. HE WAS GIVEN CHANGE OF CLOTHES BY RUETGERS NEASE AND CONTINUED TO WORK. HE DID NOT WANT ANY MEDICAL ATTENTION. I RESPONDED THE FOLLOWING DAY AND FOUND ALL MANWAY COVER BOLTS LOOSE AND GASKET STRETCHED. I TIGHTENED DOWN MANWAY AND SUPERVISED THE SWITCH WITH THE CAR THE FOLLOWING DAY. NO LEAKAGE WAS NOTED. I AM CURRENTLY IN CONVERSATION WITH SHIPPER REGARDIGN THEIR LOADING PROCEDURE.

column168: AT THE TIME AND DATE STATED IN THIS REPORT, THE CARGO TANK UNIT STARTED INTO AN UPHILL, LEFT TURN @ STATED LOCATION) WHEN HIS R/F STEERING TIRE DROPPED OFF THE HIGHWAY PAVEMENT. NORTHWEST AIRLING FLT. 3127, OPERATED BY MESABA AIRLINES/BOARDED FOR DEPARTURE WHEN THE FLIGHT CREW NOTICED A FLUID LEAK ACCOMPANIED BY FOUL VAPORS IN THE AREA OF THE FWD. CARGO COMPARTMENT.  THE AIRCRAFT WAS DEBOARDED, SECURED AND LEFT TO VENTILATE. THE SPILLED LIQUID, IDENTIFIED BY THE OWNER WHO WAS ENROUTE TO MARQUETTE, WAS J.O. STEVENS ROOF SEAM PRIMER, WHIC CONSISTS OF 90% TRICHLOROETHYLEN AND 10% SYNTHETIC RUBBER.  TEH FAILED PACKAGE WAS ORIGINALLY CHECKED THROUGH ANOTHER CARRIER IN PITTSBURGH AND TRANSFERRED TO NORTHWEST AIRLINK IN DETROIT.  THIS PACKAGE WAS VOID OF ANY SECONDARY CONTAINMENT, ABSORBANT MATERIAL, LABELING, OR SHIPPING DOCUMENTATION. MAINTENANCE PERSONNEL WERE DISPATCHED TO THE AIRCRAFT FOR SPILL CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL.  MESABA AIRLINES PROHIBITS THE CARRIAGE, STORING, OR HANDLING OF HAZARDOUS MATERIALS ONBOARD COMPANY AIRCRAFT DURING SHCEDULED PASSENGER SERVICE, SINCE THIS PACKAGE WAS NOT DECLARED AS HAZARDOUS AND, TRANSFERRED FROM ANOTHER CARRIER, MESABA DID NOT KNOWINGLY SHIP THIS PRODUCT. COMPANY DIRECTIVES AND PROCEDURES ARE IN PLACE TO HELP PREVENT TRHIS TYPE OF OCCURRENCE.

COMMERCIAL PETROLEUM ORDERED 7200 GALLONS OF DIESEL FOR STATESVILLE BRICK. PETROLEUM EXPRESS DELIVERED THE PRODUCT. THE STATESVILLE BRICK PERSONNEL TOLD THE DRIVER WHICH TANK TO PUMP THE PRODUCT INTO WHICH WAS AN ABOVE GROUND TANK (HORIZONTAL) WITHOUT ANY GAUGES. THE DRIVER DID NOT MEASURE THE TANK BECAUSE THE CUSTOMER ALWAYS ORDERS WHEN THE TANK IS EMPTY: HOWEVER, DUE TO AN ERROR IN THE ORDERING THE PRODUCT WAS SUPPOSE TO BE FOR A FUEL OIL TANK AND NOT THE DIESEL. THEREFORE THE DIESEL TANK WAS HALF FULL I.E. THE DRIVER OVERFILLED THE TANK. THE ESTIMATED 150 GALLONS WAS ALL CONTAINED IN THE AREA AROUND THE TANK AS THERE WERE CONTAINMENT WALLS. ALL THE CONTAMINATED PRODUCT AND SOIL WAS IMMEDIATELY REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH FRESH SOIL. EPA WAS NOTIFIED AND SATISFIED WITH THE CLEANUP.

DRIVER, FREDDIE HILL, TURNED INTO LANE FOR UNLOADING AT ENTRANCE. THE TIES HOLDING THE DEWAR CAME UNDONE RESULTING IN THE CYLINDER TURNING OVER INSIDE THE VAN. HE IMMEDIATELY STOPPED THE VEHICLE AND OPENED THE BACK DOOR. THERE WAS NO DAMAGE TO THE CANNISTER NOR ANY FOAMING. HOSPITAL PERSONNEL CONTACTED THE W.M.F.D. WHEREUPON THEY LIFTED THE DEWAR TO AN UPRIGHT POSITION. CAPTEIN ROGERS OF THE DEPARTMENT STATED TO ME THAT WE WERE NOT NEGLEGENT IN HANDLING THE MATERIAL AND THE ACCIDENT WAS A "FREAK" ONE, WITH NO REASON FOR PANIC. UNFORTUNATELY, THE TIES CAME UNDONE.

column168: THE ABOVE-MENTIONED DRIVER WAS PREPARING TO MAKE A DELIVERY AT THE AUBURN, ME LOCATION WHEN THE INCIDENT OCCURRED.  AS HE WAS REMOVING THE COVER FROM THE DISCHARGE LINE HE NOTICED THAT THE VALVE WAS WIDE OPEN FROM HIS PREVISOU DELIVERY.  HE IMMEDIATELY CLOSED THE VALVE WITH APPROXIMATELY 5-10 GALLONS DISCHARGING ONTO THE PAVEMENT.  HE CLEANED UP THE PUDDLE WITH SOME ABSORBENT PADS THAT HE CARRIES ON THE TRUCK.  HE THEN SUMMONED THE STATION ATTENDANT TO LOOK THE SITUATION OVER.  SHE THEN CALLED THE FIRE DEPT.AS AN ADDED PRECAUTION.  THE FIRE DEPT. SPRAYED SOME WATER ON THE SPILL AREA, THEN LEFT THE SCENE.  THE DRIVER THEN NOTIFIED ME BY TELEPHONE.  I, IN TURN, NOTIFIED THE STATE D.E.P. OF THE SITUATION. THE DRIVER WAS ISSUED A VERBAL WARNING ON BEHALF OF MOBIL OIL.  HE WAS ALSO COUNCILED BY A MOBIL FLEET INSTRUCTOR.

WHILE DEPARTING RIGBY  YARD TRAIN PO-RU WAS OBSERVED WITH CGTX 70560 AS REAR CAR.  VISUAL INSPECTION REVEALED PRODUCT RESIDUE ON SIDE OF CAR JUST BELOW AREA OF SAFETY VENT.  CAR WAS SET OUT OF TRAIN AND PLACED ON REPAIR TRACK.  CANADIAN ELECTROLIC ZINC NOTIFIED AND RESPONDED TO MAKE REPAIRS. RUPTURE DISK REPLACED ON 08/27/92, CAR FORWARDED TO CONSIGNEE.

CAR WAS PLACED ON TRACK 18 IN YARD AND SECURED. AQUALON RESPONDED ON 08/26 AND REPLACED BLOWN RUPTURE DISK.  FAILURE CAUSED BY PRODUCT SPLASHING AGAINST DISK DURING CAR MOVEMENT.  A DESIGN CHANGE IS NEEDED TO PREVENT DISK FAILURES CAU SED BY SPLASHING PRODUCT.

column168: AT 0200 HOURS ON AUGUST 2, 1992 AN ITS EMPLOYEE IN THE PROCESS OF GROUNDING TRAILER SFTU 688420 FROM FLAT CAR TTAX 767723 WHICH ARRIVED AT CONRAIL'S 47TH STREET TRAILVAN ON TRAIN TV-1, REPORTED OBSERVING A SMALL LEAK EMITTING FROM THE TRAILER.  O.H. MATERIALS WAS CALLED AND ARRIVED AT 800 HOURS. THE CHICAGO FIRE DEPARTMENT AND THE EPA WERE NOTIFIED.  OH MATERIALS OPENED THE DOORS AND FOUND ONE 55 GAL.CDRUM LEAKING FROM THE BOTTOM. THE TRAILER WAS LOADED WIT 80 (55 GAL) DRUMS AND APPARENTLY 8 OF THE DRUMS WERE DOUBLE STACKED ON TOP OF THE OTHER DRUMS WITH A MAKE SHIFT BULKHEAD FOR SECURING THE 8 DRUMS.  APPARENTLY DURING TRANSPORTATION ONE OF THE DRUMS BROKE THROUGH THE BULKHEALD AND ROLLED UP AND DOEN THE LOWER DRUMS. EVENTUALLY THE DRUM BECAME DAMAGED TO THE EXTENT IT BEGAN LEAKING PRODUCT ON THE OTHER DRUMS.  OH MATERIALS OVERPACKED THE DAMAGED DRUM, CLEANED AND TRANSFERRED THE REMAINING 79 DRUMS INTO TRAILER SKRZ 220763.

AT APPROXIMATELY 130 HOURS MONDAY AUGUST 3, 1992, CONRAIL EMPLOYEES IN THE PROCESS OF DELIVERING TANK CAR GATX-10049 TO THE CSXT INTERCHANGE TRACK IN BALTIMORE, MD REPORTED OBSERVING LIQUID PRODUCT NEAR THE TOP OF THE VALVE ASSEMBLY.  CHEMTREC AND THE SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED. AT 1100 HOURS, AUGUST 3, 1992, PERSONNEL FROM HERCULES RESPONDED TO BAY. VIEW YARD AND UPON INSPECTION OF THE TANK CAR FOUND A RUPTURED FRANGIBLE DISK IN TH CAR'S SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  THE RUPTURED DISK WAS REMOVED AND REPLACED WITH A COMPATIBLE 100 POUND RATED FRANGIBLE DIS.  CAR WAS RELEASED TO DESTINATION AT 1400 HOURS, AUGUST 3, 1992.

column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 300 HOURS, MONDAY, AUGUST 10, 1992, A CONRAIL CAR INSPECTOR OUTBOUND TRAIN PIEDO REPORTED OBSERVING A SMALL LEAK (ESTIMATED AT 1 PINT PER MINUTE) FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET OF GATX 5578. DRIVER WAS PUMPING PRODUCT OFF TRUCK ON ONE SIDE OF THE TRUCK WHEN ON THE OPPOSITE SIDE THE CAP CAME OFF WHERE THE OTHER PUMP OFF LINE IS LOCATED. THE CAP HAD 2 CANS THAT SECURE THE CAP; HOWEVER; THE VIBRATION OF THE PUMP CAUSED THE EARS TO OPEN, I.E., THE CAP CAME OFF THE LINE RESULTING IN APPROX 75 GALLONS SPILLAGE.  ALL THE PRODUCT WAS CLEANED UP AND THE CONTAMINATED SOIL VEMONED WITHIN 2 HOURS.  ALL WAS APPROVED BY THE EPA. TO PREVENT THIS TYPE INCIDENT IN THE FUTRE WE HAVE SECURED EACH CAP BY LOCKING THE EARS TOGETHER WHILE ON THE PUMP OFF LINES.

ADVISED BY CSX OPS. CTR. THAT THE YARD CREW WAS SWITCHING CAR FLIX 2576 AN NOTICED A SLIGHT SPLASH FROM THE TOP FITTINGS OF THE CAR. YD CREW ISOLATED THE CAR IN #29 TRACK WINSTON YD.  CHEMTREC WAS CONTACTED FOR SHIPPER ASSISTANCE.  SHIPPER'S REP ADVISED HE WOULD HAVE PERSONNEL RESPOND. FARMLAND PERSONNEL INSPECTED CAR AND FOUND A RUPTURED SAFETY VENT DISC. RECEIVED REPORT THAT FRA SUSPECTOR OBSERVED A LEAKING TANK CAR IN YARD AT MOBILE TANK CAR REPORTED TO HAVE A SLIGHT DRIP FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET CAP. THE CAR WAS ISOLATED AND THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED BY CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR PERSONNEL TO RESPOND.  THEY PLACED A NEW GASKET IN THE OUTLET CAP AND TIGHTENED CAP DOWN.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED AND THE CAR RELEASED 1330 ON 9/01/92.

THE CARGO TANK WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING (A SLIGHT DRIP) UPON ITS ARRIVAL AT THE CONSIGNEE.  THE PRODUCT BEING RELEASED WAS CONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA.  THE PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK AND WAS THEN SUCCESSFULLY DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEES STORAGE TANK. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.  THE LEAKING CARGO TANK WAS REMOVED FROM SERVICE PENDING REPAIRS.

PRODUCT HAD BEEN SUCCESSFULLY DELIVERED FROM CARRIER'S CARGO TANK TO THE CONSIGNEE'S STORAGE TANK VIA CARRIER HOSES.  AS THE DRIVER WAS PUTTING AWAY HIS PRODUCT TRANSFER HOSES, APPROXIMATELY ONE-HALF GALLON SPILLED FROM A HOSE TO THE GROUND. CONSIGNEE PERSONNEL CLEANED UP THE SPILLED MATERIAL.
WHILE THIS WAS BEING LOADED, THE DRUM SLIPPED OUT OF THE DOCKWORKER'S HANDS AND FELL OVER THE LID.  BENT ON IMPACT, CONTENTS SPILLED OUT.

DURING A ROUTINE BREAK AT A REST AREA, OUR DRIVER DISCOVERED A LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE REAR DRAIN HOLES OF THE TRAILER.  THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY SECURED THE AREA AROUND HIS VEHICLE, PLACED SAND ON THE SPILLED MATERIAL AND CONTACTED THE COMPANY. THE LOCAL AUTHORITIES WERE CALLED TO HELP CONTROL THE SCENE AND A CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR WAS CALLED TO CLEAN UP THE SPILL.  IT WAS DISCOVERED BY THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR THAT ONE 5-GALLON CONTAINER OF MATERIAL HAD RUPTURED INSIDE ITS CARDBOARD BOX.  THE RUPTURE WAS NOT CAUSED BY ANY VISIBLE EXTERNAL CONDITION.  THE LEAKING MATERIAL LEAKED DOWN ONTO 43 OTHER IDENTICAL CARDBOARD BOXES STACKED UNDERNEATH THE LEAKING CONTAINER.  THE CLEAN UP CONTRACTOR OVERPACKED THE LEAKING CONTAINER IN A SALVAGE DRUM.  THE CONTAMINATED CARDBOARD BOXES WERE STRIPPED OFF THE POLYETHYLENE CONTAINERS AND BURNED AT THE SCENE UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT.  THE REMAINING POLYETHYLENE LINERS WERE OVERPACKED AND THE ENTIRE SHIPMENT WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPACKAGING.  THE FREE MATERIAL IN THE TRAILER WAS WASHED O UT WITH A SOLUTION OF DETERGENT AND WATER.

THE DRIVER TOOK HIS UNIT OFF THE ROAD AT THE EARLIEST OPPARTUNITY TO EXAMINE THE CARGO TANK. THE PRODUCT WAS DETERMINED TO HAVE BEEN RELEASED THROUGH A FAILED RUPTURE DISC ON THE CARGO TANK. THE CAUSE OF THE CAILURE REMAINS UNKNOWN. THE PRODUCT IS NOT TRANSPORTED UNDER ANY APPLIED PRESSURE. CLEAN UP OF THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IMPOSSIBLE DUE TO THE RAIN. THE RUPTURE DISC HAS BEEN REPLACED.

column168: OUR TRAACTOR-TRAILER WAS INVOLVED IN A ACCIDENT WHICH APPARENTLY CAUSED A FIRE.  THE FIRE ENGULFED THE ENTIRE TRACTOR AND THEY BURNT THE FRON TPORTION OF THE TRAILER IT WAS PULLING.  THE HIGH TEMPERATURE OF THIS FIRE CREATED A CRACK IN ONE OF THE COMPARTMENT'S INTERNAL VALVE AND THIS ALLOWED THE KEROSENE SPILLAGE.  TERRA ENVIRONMENTAL CORPORATIONWAS HIRED TO REMOVE THE 2900 ALLONS OF KEROSENE STILL INSIDE OUR TANKER AND TO EXCAVATE THE CONTAMINATED SOIL.  THE CONTAMINATED SOIL WAS TRANSPORTED TO ORCHARD HILLS SANCTUARY LANDFILL FOR DISPOSAL.

THE DRIVER OF VEHICLE #1 PARKED HIS UNIT ON CALDRE ST. AND WENT INTO A RESTAURANT.  WHEN HE RETURNED TO THE TRUCK HE DISCOVERED PRODUCT LEAKING FROM THE TRAILER.  THE LOCAL POLICE DEPARTMENT WAS THEN CALL TO THE SCENE. THE POLICE DEPARTMENT, NO TKNOWING WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS, CALLED IN A HAZ MAT CLEAN-UP CREW AS WELL AS THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT TO ASSIST. AUTHORITIES AT RHONE-POULENC WERE CALLED TO INFORM THE FIRE DEPARTMENT EXACTLY WHAT THE PRODUCT WAS DO PROPER CLEAN-UP COULD BE ADMINISTERED. UPON OPENING THE TRAILER DOORS, THEY DISCOVERED THAT THE INNER POLY-LINER IN THE DRUMS RUPTURED CAUSING THE PRODUCT TO SEEP BETWEEN THE LINER AND THE STEEL PART OF THE DRUM AND OUT THE 3/4" SIDE BUNG.  THE FIRE MARSHALL TIGHTENED THE BUNGS AND PUT AND ABSORBANT COMPOUND ON THE SPILL.  THE DRIVER WAS THEN INSTRUCTED TO CONTINUE ON TO HIS DESTINATION TO NEWARK, NJ.  ONCE THE DRIVER ARRIVED, AUTHORITIES PUT THE DAMAGED DRUMS IN 85 GALLON RECOVERY DRUM TO BE SHIPPED BACK TO THE RHONE-POULENC IN SPARTANBURG, PA.

AT THE TIME OF ORDERING A SUPPLY OF FUEL, THE RYDER COMPANY PERSONNEL KNEW THATTHE GAUGE IN THIER STORAGE TANK WAS INOPERATIVE. AT THE TIME OF THE AMDELIVERY, THE DRIVER CONTACTED DISPATCH NOTIFYING HIM THAT THE GAUGE DID NOTWORK. DISPATCH TOLD HIM TO PUMP AT THE LOWEST R.P.M. SO THAT IF AN OVERFILL DIDOCCUR IT WOULD BE AT A MINIMUM. DISPATCH CONFIRMED THAT RYDER HAD MADE UP THEGALLONS REQUESTED AND THAT THEY SHOULD KNOW IF AMOUNT COULD BE ACCEPTED.NEEDLESS TO DAY, ALL ASSESSMENTS WERE WRONG AND THE OVERFILL AND SPILLOCCURRED. BECUASE OF THE FACT THAT THE SIGHT GAUGE WAS INOPERATIVE AT THE TIMEOFDELIVERY, THE STORAGE TANK WAS OVERFILLED.

column168: THE DRIVER LOADED AT CWM RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC. IN W. CARROLLTON, OHIO, AND ASHE DEPARTED THE CWM FACILITY, HIS PAPERWORK FELL OFF THE TRUCK SEAT. WHEN THEDRIVER REACHED FOR THE PAPERWORK, THE VEHICLE DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT AND THERIGHT WHEELS DROPPED OFF THE PAVED ROADWAY INTO A DEEP DITCH. THE DRIVER WASUNABLE TO RECOVER AND THE TRACTOR AND THE TRAILER ROLLED ONTO ITS RIGHT SIDE.BECAUSE THE ACCIDENT OCCURRED ADJACENT TO THE CWM FACILITY, CWM PERSONNEL ANDEQUIPMENT WERE ON THE SCENE IMMEDIATELY. THE CONTENTS OF THE TANKER WASTRANSFERRED INTO VACUUM TANKERS AND THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER WERE TOWED. THETRAILER WAS PARKED IN THE CWM COMPOUND. BASED UPON WEIGHT, A TOTAL OF 69.2GALLONS OF MATERIAL WAS SPILLED. THE PRODUCT COMPOSITION WAS 99.77 PERCENTWATER AND .23 PERCENT METHANOL AND ETHANOL. THE DRIVER SUBMITTED TO A DRUG TESTON AUGUST 28, 1992; RESULTS WERE NEGATIVE.
HEAVY ON LIGHT, CANS WERE CRUSHED.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSFERRED TO A RECOVERY PAIL AND DELIVERED TO CONSIGNEE.

column168: RECEIVED REPORT FROM TRAINMASTER IN TOLEDO ON THAT A TANKC AR WAS VENTING VAPORS; NO EVIDENCE OF A LIQUID LEAK.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED BY CHEMTREC.  THE SHIPPER NOTIFIED THE CONSIGNNE BECAUSE THE CAR HADB EEND ELIVERED TO A BULK DISTRIBUTION TRANSFER TERMINAL.  THE CONSIGNEE HAD THE TER MINAL INSPECT THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE UNLOADING APPARTENANCES HAD NOT BEEN TIGHTLY CLOSED AFTER TAKING OFF A LOAD ALLOWING FOR MINOR VAPOR LEAK.  THE CLOSURES WERE TIGHTLY SECURED AND THE VAPOR RELEASE WAS STOPPED.

THE GENERAL CAR FOREMAN AT HAMLET, NC. NOTIFIED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS GROUP THAT HE HAD BEEN ADVISED THAT THE SC CENTRAL RR HAD REJECTED 8 TANK CARS IN INTERCHANGE AT CHERAW, SC, DUE TO SEVERE CORROSION ON TOP OF THE CARS.  CSXT INSPECTED THE CARS AND CONFIRMED THAT ALL THE CARS HAD EXTENSIVE CORROSION TO MANWAYS, SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLIES, AND LIQUID EDUCTION LINES.  THE CARS WERE MOVED BACK TO HAMLET, NC, AND THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS. REPAIRS INCLUDED REPLACING BLOWN RUPTURE DISKS, REPLACING BAD MANWAY GASKETS, AND TIGHTENING LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS.  IN ADDITION, SEVERAL MANWAY BOLTS WERE CORRODED OFF OR FROZEN. THERE WAS NO OBVIOUS SIGNS OF LIQUID LEAKS ON THE CARS ALTHOUGH THE EXTENSIVE CORROSION WAS EVIDENCE THAT ALL THE CARS HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN IN A LEAKING CONDITION.  CSXT'S GENERAL FOREMAN ACCOMPANIED BY AN FRA I NSPECTOR INSPECTED THE CARS TO CONFIRM REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED.

CSXT INSPECTED THE CARS AND CONFIRMED THAT ALL THE CARS HAD EXTENSIVE CORROSION TO MANWAYS, SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLIES, AND LIQUID EDUCTION LINES.  THE CARS WERE MOVED BACK TO HAMLET, NC, AND THE SHIPPER ARRANGED FOR A RAIL CAR REPAIR COMPANY TO RESPOND TO MAKE REPAIRS. REPAIRS INCLUDED REPLACING BLOWN RUPTURE DISKS, REPLACING BAD MANWAY GASKETS, AND TIGHTENING LOOSE MANWAY BOLTS.  IN ADDITION, SEVERAL MANWAY BOLTS WERE CORRODED OFF OR FROZEN. THERE WAS NO OBVIOUS SIGNS OF LIQUID LEAKS ON THE CARS ALTHOUGH THE EXTENSIVE CORROSION WAS EVIDENCE THAT ALL THE CARS HAD PREVIOUSLY BEEN IN A LEAKING CONDITION.  CSXT'S GENERAL FOREMAN ACCOMPANIED BY AN FRA I NSPECTOR INSPECTED THE CARS TO CONFIRM REPAIRS HAD BEEN COMPLETED.

AT 1:30 AM ON AUGUST 17, 1992 A BROMINE RELEASE OCCURED AT THE ABOVE LOCATION.  APPROXIMATELY 60 POUNDS OF ELEMENTAL BROMINE WAS RELEASED ONTO A CONCRETE AREA AS A RESULT OF THE OVERFILLING OF A BROMINE TANKER TRUCK. THE TEMPERATURE WAS 57 DEGREES F WITH CLEAR SKIES AND A SLIGHT SOUTHERN WIND.  THE LOW TEMPERATURE AND WEATHER CONDITIONS WERE SUCH THAT THE MAJORITY OF THE BROMINE REMAINED THE LIQUID STATE WITH ONLY A SMALL AMOUNT VAPORIZING.  THE BROMINE VAPORS WERE CONTAINED WITHIN THE PLANT SITE.  THE LIQUFIED BROMINE WITHIN THE CONTAINMENT WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODIUM THIOSULFATE AND SODA ASH;  THIS SOLUTION WAS PUMPED BACK INTO THE BRINE SYSTEM FOR DISPOSAL.  THIS INCIDENT OCCURRED AS A RESULT OF OPERATOR ERROR; THE OPERATOR MISREAD THE TANK WEIGHT AND PROGRAMMED A LOADING VALUE THAT WAS TOO HIGH, RESULTING IN A TRUCK OVERFILL.  THE SOP FOR THIS ACTION HAS BEEN REVIEWED AND DETERMINED TO BE SOUND AND ACCURATE.  OPERATORS HAVE BEEN RE-TRAINED AS A RESULT OF THIS ACCIDENT.

THE INCIDENT WAS CAUSED BY DRUM FAILURE AT THE SEAM AT THE BOTTOM OF THE DRUM.  MATERIAL EXITING THE TRAILER RAN OVER THE FLAT PLATE ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE SUMP GRATE.  THIS PLATE EXITING THE TRAILER RAN OVER THE FLAT PLATE ON THE LEFT SIDE OF THE SUMP GRATE.  THIS PLATE HAS DRAIN HOLES CUT INT IT, THESE SLOTS HAVE BEEN ENLARGED AND A DIKING, DIRECTIONAL PIECE OF ANGLE IRON HAS BEEN ADDED.  RECOVERED 28 GAL FROM THE TRUCK SUMP.  APPROX 20 GAL REMAINED IN THE DRUM, APPROX 1 QT ON BLACKTOP AT SRM, APPROX 1/2 GAL CLEANED UP A NICOLAY'S RESIDENCE.

ON 8-19-92 AT APPROX 0217 HRS, I, KAREN NICHOLS (HAZ MAT COORD) OF ABX AIR, INC. 145 HUNTER DR, WILMIMGTON, OH 45177, INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT OF HAZ MATERAILS. THE SHIPMENT WAS DISCOVERED IN SECONDARY 2 OF OUR SORT FACILITY BY MIKE AEH (SORT SUPV). THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A FBREBOARD BOX. THERE WERE PREPRINTED ARROWS ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX INDICATING PROPER ORIENTATION OF THE MATERIALS INSIDE. THERE WERE NO HAZ MARKINGS OR LABELS ON THE FIBREBOARD BOX, NOR DID IT HAVE A SHIPPER'S CERT. ACCOMPANYING IT. INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE SEVERAL BROKEN GLASS BOTTLES. THE NUMBER OF BOTTLES AND CONTENTS OF EACH WERE DIFFICULT TO ASSESS AS THE PRODUCT THAT SPILLED, SMEARED SOME OF THE LABELS AND THE GLASS BOTTLES WERE BADLY SHATTERED. FROM THE SHIPPER'S LETTER INSIDE THE SHIPMENT AND THE UNBROKEN GLASS BOTTLES, I DISCOVERED THE SHIPMENT TO CONTAIN APPROX. 49 TOTAL ONCES OF AFTERSHAVE SAMPLES AND FRAGRANCE OILS. ALSO IN THIS SHIPMENT WERE 9 AEROSOL CANS OF COLOGNE (NONE OF WHICH LEAKED). 8 WERE OF 1 OZ. CAPACITY AND 1 WAS OF 2 OZ. CAPACITY. THERE WERE NO ABSORBENT MATERIALS USED. STYROFOAM PACKING PEANUTS WERE USED. THE PRODUCTS THAT LEAKED DISSOLVED THE PACKING PEANUTS. THIS SHIPMENT IS CURRENTLY BEING HELD IN OUR HAZ MAT SECURITY CAGE UNDER LOCK AND KEY. IT HAS BEEN REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM PENDING RELEASE BY THE FAA.

column168: THERE WAS NO PACKAGING FAILURE OF ANY KIND ASSOCIATED WITH THIS INCIDENT. THIS INVOLVED THE BULK DELIVERY OF GASOLINE TO A CONVENIENCE STORE AND IS CAUSED BY HUMAN ERROR.  OUR DRIVER MEASURED THE BELOW GROUND STORAGE TAN K TO MAKE SURE THE GAS HE BAD BROUGHT WOULD FIT.  BUT WHEN HE CONVERTED THE STICK READINGS TO GALLONS, HE USED A TANK CHART FOR THE WRONG DIAMETER TANK.  THIS LED HIM TO BELIEVE THAT HE HAD ROOM FOR MORE GAS THAN HE DID. WHEN THE TANK GOT FULL, AN ESTIMATED 10 GALLONS CAME OUT THE CAP ON THE OTHER END OF THE TANK BEFORE OUR DRIVER WAS ABLE TO STOPTHE FLOW.  CALY ABSORBANTS WERE USED TO CLEAN THE GAS OFF THE BLACKTOP.  THE NEW YORK STATE DEPT OF ENVIRONMENTAL CONSERVATION WAS NOTIFIED AND ASSIGNED A REFERENCE #9206224 TO THIS INCIDENT.

column42: PAINT INCLUDING PAINT, LACQUER, ENAMEL, STAIN, SHELLAC SOLUTIONS, VARNISH, POLISH, LIQUID FILLER AND LIQUID LACQUER BASE
column168: PASSEMGER MRS. EDUARDO GUEVARO CHECKED AS BAGGAGE UNMARKED BOX ON FLIGHT 4640 IN COLUMBIA SC CONNECTING TO FLIGHT 1899 IN BNA.  FINAL DESTINATION HOUSTON, TX.  PASSENGER WAS QUESTIONED AS TO CONTENTS OF BOX AND SPECIFICALLY IF IT CONTAINED HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  PASSENGER STATED IT DID NOT.  ON ARRIVAL OF FLIGHT 1899 IN HOUSTON, PAINT WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE BOX.  THERE WAS NOT VISIBLE DAMAGE TO BOX.  BOX WAS REMOVED FROM AFT CARGO AREA ON AIRCRAFT FOR INSPECTION.  BOX WAS OPENED AND ONE GALLON CAN OF WHITE SEI-GLASS ENAMEL OIL BASE PAINT WAS DISCOVERED.  ALSO A ONE GALLON PLASTIC CONTAINER OF PAINT THINNER.  THE LID ON THE PAINT CAN WAS LOOSE AND MOST OF THE CONTENTS HAD LEAKED OUT.  THE ONE GALLON OF PAINT THINNER DID  NOT APPEAR TO HAVE LOST ANY OF ITS CONTENTS.

column42: BATTERY FLUID, ACID, WITH BATTERY, ELECTRIC STORAGE, WET, EMPTY, OR DRY
column168: ON 8-8-92 AT APPROXIMATELY 0324 HOURS, I, KAREN NICHOLS (HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR), OF ABX AIR, INC., INVESTIGATED A LEAKING SHIPMENT IN THE HAZ MAT AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY.  THE SHIPMENT WAS BROUGH TO MY ATTENTION BY RHONDA CLONCH (HAS-MAT LEAD), WHO OPENED THIS SHIPMENT TO CONFIRM IT DID CONTAIN A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL.  THE BOX WAS MARKED AND LABELED FOR CORROSIVE MATERIAL BUT WAS NOT ACCOMPANIED BY A SHIPPER CERTIFICATION. ON.  THE SHIPMENT WAS PACKAGED IN A DOT 12-B-65 FIBREBOARD BOX.  INSIDE THE FIBREBOARD BOX WERE 2 MORE DOT 12B-65 FIBREBOARD BOXES CONTAINING 1 EACH MOTORCYCLE BATTERIES.  ALSO, INSIDE THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WERE 2 X 32 OZ. PLASTIC BOTTLES WITH PLASTIC SCREW TYPE CLOSURES, CONTAINING BATTERY ACID.  ONE OF THE 2 PLASTIC BOTTLES LEAKED APPROXIMATELY 2 OZ. OF BATTERY ACID.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS UNDETERMINABLE. THE OUTER FIBREBOARD BOX WAS MARKED WITH "BATTERY FLUID", ACID, WITH BATTERY, NA2786" AND THERE WAS A CORROSIVE LABEL AFFIXED.  THERE WERE SPECIFICATION ORIENTATION ARROWS PREPRINTED ON 2 OPPOSITE SIDES WITH "THIS SIDE UP" PREPRINTED ON THE TOP OF THE FIBREBOARD BOX.  NONE OF THE INNER PACKAGINGS HAD ANY HAZARD MARKING OR LABELS ON THEM. THIS SHIPMENT HAS BEEN REPACKED IN A D.O.T. APPROVED RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED TO DESTINATION ACCOMPANIED BY A SHIPPER'S CERTIFICATION PROVIDED BY THE SHIPPER.

AT 0347 SORT LEAD, MARK COY, REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMITTING A STRONG ODOR. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I, TONY FRYE, HAZ MAT COORDINATOR, AND ADDIE CAMPTON, PART-TIME HAZ MAT TECHNICIAN, INVESTIGATED THE SHIPMENT. ADDIE DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE MASK TO INVESTIGATE THE CONTENTS. INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE FIVE, ONE QUART, METAL, FRICTION TYPE CONTAINERS. ALSO THREE TUBES WITH SCREWW TYPE CLOSURES. THERE WAS NO MEANS TO SECURE THE FRICTION TYPE CONTAINERS. THE SHIPMENT WAS HELD AT THE HAZ MAT SORT PENDING ARRIVAL OF THE INFORMATION ON IT, I, TONY FRYE, OBTAINED THE TRANSPORT DETAILS. THE FIVE METAL FRICTION TYPE CONTAINERS CONTAINED A FLAMMABLE LIQUID AND THE THREE TUBES CONTAINED AN OXIDIZER. THERE WAS NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANYING THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS. THIS SHIPMENT IS IN THE HAZ MAT SORT IN THE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS CABINET PENDING RELEASE BY THE (FHWA) FDERAL HIGHWAY ADMINISTRATION. A COPY OF THE MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET IS ATTACHED TO THIS REPORT.

THIS WAS TIGHTENED W/36" WRENCH, STOPPING LEAK. FURTHER INSPECTION OF TOP OPERATED VALVE HANDLE REVEALED 3/4 TURN OPEN AND PACKING NOT FULLY TIGHTENED. I WAS ADVISED BY CHENTREC THAT THE HIALEAH FIRE DEPT. AND POLICE DEPT. WERE ON THE SCENE OF A VAPOR CLOUD REPORTED AS COMING FROM A LEAKING TANK CAR RCRX 1092; THEY WERE REQUESTING INFORMATION REGARDING A SHIPPING DOCUMENTS AND CHEMICAL INFORMATION. REPORTED THAT SEVERAL PERSONS WERE ATTEMPTING TO SECURE THE CAR IN THE REAR OF U.S. CHLORINE AT 36ST AVE. IN HIALEAH, FLORIDA. THE PERSONS WORKING ON THE CAR FAILD TO GIVE ANY INFORMATION ABOUT THE INCIDENT TO THE FIRE DEPT. AND LEFT THE AREA, AT WHCIH TIME A VAPOR CLOUD STARTED TO FORM ABOVE THE CAR. PERSONNEL WORKING ON THE CAR 1ST TOLD THE FIRE DEPT. THAT THE INCIDENT WAS ON THE F.E.C. RAILROAD. I CONTACTED THE F.E.C. DISPATCHER WHO ADVISED THAT THE INCIDENT WAS NOT ON THEIR RAILROAD, AND THAT THE TRACKAGE BEHIND U.S. CHLORINE WAS OPERATED BY CSX. CSX OPERATION CENTER WAS CONTACTED AND ADVISED OF THE INCIDENT. TRAINMASTER GEORGE HART WAS CONTACTED AND REQUESTED TO RESPOND TO THE AREA TO DETERMINE IF THE INCIDENT WAS ON CSX PROPERTY. CONTACT WAS MADE WITH THE HIALEAH FIRE DEPT. MR. MARK HOPKINS AT THE SCENE WHO REQUESTED SHIPPING DOCUMENTS ON CAR RCRX 1092.

ON THURSDAY, 7/30/92, OUR WAREHOUSE RECEIVED A STEAMSHIP CONTAINER (HDMU409802-6) WITH VARIOUS GENERAL COMMODITIES FOR VARIOUS CONSIGNEES FOR UNLOADING.  OUR WAREHOUSEMEN STARTED TO UNLOAD THE CONTAINER WHEN THEY STARTED TO SMELL A BAD ODOR.  THEY REPORTED THIS INCIDENT TO THE SUPERVISOR, WHO IMMEDIATELY HAD THE CONTAINER CLOSED, SEALED AND PLACED IN OUR TRUCKING YARD.  THERE WAS NO VISIBLE NOTICE OF ANY SPILL AT THE TIME. MANAEMENT DECIDED TO HIRE A HAZARDOUS WASTE SPECIALIST, CLEAN VENTURE, TO UNLOAD THE CONTAINER. SINCE THE CARGO WAS UNDER US CUSTOMS SERVICE BOND AND THERE WAS NO IMMINENT DANGER THE APPOROVAL PROCESS TOOK A LITTLE TIME.  AFTER US CUSTOMS APPROIVAL, CLEAN VENTURE BEGAN THE PROCESS OF UNLOADING AND DETERMINING IF THERE WAS A SPILL ON AUGUST 12, 1992.  THEY FINISHED THE PROCESS BY AUGUST 14, 1992.  THEY DECONTAMINATED THE STEAMSHIP CONTAINER AND PLACED THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS WITHIN DRUMS AT OUR TERMINAL.  THE PRODUCTS HAVE BEEN SECURED IN A STORAGE TRAILER WAITING FOR APPROVAL TO DISPOSE OF THEM.  THE ENTIRE CLEAN UP AND DISPOSAL WILL BE CONDUCTED BY CLEAN VENTURE. SINCE OUR PERSONNEL DID NOT UNLOAD THE CARGO, IT IS DIFFICULT TO ANSWER ITEMS VII AND VIII ACCURATELY.  IF THERE ARE SPECIFIC QUESTIONS ON THE SPILL, YOU CAN CONTACT MR. MARK DOUGHERTY OF CLEAN VENTURE (201-340-8200). IN ADDITION, SINCE THE PRODUCT HAD NOT BEEN DESTROYED, THERE IS NO HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST TO ATTACH.  I WILL FORWARD THE MANIFEST TO YOUR OFFICE ONCE IT IS RECEIVED. IF THERE ARE ANY QUESTIONS, PLEASE CONTACT ME.

column168: SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) J. JARA WAS NOTIFIED THAT HOPPER CAR NAHX 55364 HAD DERAILED AT THE OROVILLE FREIGHT YARD.  SA/HM JARA RESPONDED AND MET WITH OROVILLE BATTALION CHIEF R. E. ZOLLNER ON THE SCENE.  THE YARD OPERATIONS HAD BEEN SHUT DOWN AND SA/HM JARA INSPECTED THE CAR.  NAHX 55364 WAS A THREE COMPARTMENT HOPPER CAR AND COMPARTMENT NUMBER THREE HAD 50-75 LBS OF PRODUCT ON THE GROUND.  TRAYNHAM TRUCKING WAS CONTACTED TO TRANSLOAD PRODUCT INTO TRUCKS SO CAR COUL BE RAILED.  A SLOW ORDER (20 MPH) WAS PLACED THROUGH THE YARD UNTIL THE CLEANUP WAS COMPLETED.  PROBLEMS WERE ENCOUNTERED DUE TO HIGHWINDS CAUSING MOVEMENT OF PRODUCT (DUST PARTICLES) DURING THE VACUUM PROCESS.  TRAYNHAM TRUCKING UNLOADED ONE COMPARTMENT BEFORE OPERATION WAS SHUT DOWN.  THE REMAINING TWO COMPARTMENTS WERE PLUGGED FOR CAR TO BE RAILED.  INDUSTRIAL CLEANING NOTIFIED AND VACUUMED COMMODITY UP.  CAR WAS RERAILED AND MOVED TO THE WEST END OF THE YARD.  REMAINING PRODUCT WAS TRANSLOADED BY FLEET TRANSPORT. CHEMTREC, OROVILLE FIRE DEPARTMENT, AND CA STATE O.E.S. WERE NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

THIS PAIL ARRIVED BIRCH RUN ON 8/25 OFF TRAILER 289144 AND WAS PLACED INTO THE MIDLAND ARREA OF OUR DOCK.  WHEN DRIVER SUMERIX WAS GIVEN HIS BILLS AND WENT TO LOAD THI PIECE, HE NOTED THAT IT WAS DENTED AND THAT THERE WAS A SMALL AMOUNT OF CONTENT LEAKING ONTO THE DOCK.  HE BROUGH THIS TO MY ATTENTION.  WE INVERTED THE PAIL, TOOK IT OUTSIDE.  AND I CALLED CHEMTREC AND DOW CORNING, AUBURN.  APPARENTL, THIS WAS TRUCK ON OUR DOCK, BUT NO-ONE SAID ANYTING, POSSIBLE BECAUSE THE RESPONSIBLE PARTY NEVER FELT THE IMPACT WHILE DOCKING OTHER FREIGHT.  THIS FREIGHT IS BEING DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE IN A RECOVERY DRUM PER THE AUTHPRITY OF KEVIN ELLIS AT 517-496-5452. PRO325721570.

column168: J. WASHINGTON UNLOADED SHPT AND SET IT IN THE LAB LOADING BAY.  ROB FOUNTAIN NOTICED A SMELL AND AFTER LOADING ONE OF THE DRUMS, NOTICED A PUDDLE LEFT ON THE DOCK.  HE CONTACTED PAUL LORENSEN AND MADE HIM AWARE OF THE SPILL.  THERE WAS NO INHALATION HAZARD SO DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM.  APPROX TWO CUPS OF LIQUID WERE LEAKED AND THIS WAS CONTAINED WITH SAND AND ALSO PLACED IN A SMALL RECOVERY DRUM.  THE DRUM CONTAINING THE PRODUCT THAT WAS LEAKING AND THE SPILLED PORTION WERE BOTH PUT ON A TRAILER AND ISOLATED ON THE YARD.  THE SHIPPER WAS CALLED AND HE IS GIVING US DISPOSITION AND AUTHORITY TO RETURN.  THE SPILLED AREA WAS CLEANED WITH STROND DETERGENT UPON IN SUTRCTIONS BY SHIPPER.  SAFETY DEPT, REGION OFFICE N OTICIED BY PHONE.  HAZ MATERIAL INCIDENT REPORT WAS SENT BY S-1.

THE GDA TERMINAL WAS NOTIFIED OF A LEAKING TRAILER ENROUTE TO THE ATLANTA C/C.  THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED TO EAT LUNCH AND NOTICED THE LEAK.  THE DRIVER CALLED ATL AND SAFETY SUPR.  JACK TISDALE NOTIFIED GDA OF THE INCIDENT.  AFTER APPROX.  30 MINUTED AND INSPECTION BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPT THE LEAK HAD STOPPED. THE DRIVER WAS TOLD BY THE FIRE DEPT THAT HE COULD PROCEED TO THE ANS TERMINAL (LESS THAN 10 MILES FROM WHERE THE DRIVER HAD STOPPED).  THE LEAKING TRAILER (17-9586) WAS UNLOADED AND THE ONE LEAKING DRUM WAS PLACED INTO A RECOVERY DRUM AND RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER PER PAT PARKER WITH THE SHIPPER. THE UPPER SIDE OF THE DRUM HAD A SMALL HOLE IN IT, APPARENTLY CAUSED BY FRICTION AGAINST ANOTHER DRUM FROM ROAD VIBRATION.  THIS WAS THE FIRST TIME THAT THE DRIVER NOTICED THE LEAK SINCE HE WAS DISPATCHED.  THERE WAS VERY LITTLE SPILLED MATERIAL TO CLEAN UP, IT EVAPORATED QUICKLY.  WHAT LITTLE MATERIAL HAD TO BE CLEANED UP WAS PLACED INTO THE RECOVERY DRUM WITH THE LEAKING DRUM.  NO HAZARDOUS WASTE WAS DISPOSED OF AT THE SPILL SITE OR AT THE ANS TERMINAL.  ONE OTHER SHPT WAS PARTIALLY CONTAMINATED, PRO 266-204061 HAD ONE BOX THAT ABSORBED A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE SPILLED LIQUID.  THE BOX WAS SENT ON TO DEST WITH THE ENTIRE SHPT.

LIQUID WAS NOTICED COMING FROM BROKEN CONTAINERS THAT HAD FALLEN FROM THE PALLET PRIOR TO LOADING THEM ON THE AIRCRAFT.  CLEANUP WAS ACCOMPLISHED WITH "SPEED DRY".  THE CONTAINERS WERE THEN PLACED IN ANOTHER PLASTIC CONTAINER AND THIS, IN TURN, WAS PLACED IN YET ANOTHER PLASTIC CONTAINER AND THEN SEALED WITH TAPE.  DISPOSAL WAS THROUGH THE COMPANY ADVANCED CLEANUP TECHNOLOGIES, INC.  PLEASE SEE ATTACED COPY OF UNIFORM HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST #92181214.

column168: THE CARRIER'S DRIVER, BILL BROWN, HAD CAUPLED HIS HOSE TO BEGIN LOADING WASTE SOLVENT. THE GASKET LOCATED AT THE END OF THE HOSE WHICH ATTACHES TO THE INTAKE COUPLING VALVE, FAILED. THE GASKET WAS SUCKED INTO THE TANK CAR. JUST AS THE GASKET FAILED, WASTE SOLVENT SPRAYED ONTO THE LOADING AREA AND DIKE WALL. THE VALVE WAS IMMEDIATELY CLOSED BUT APPROXIMATELY THREE GALLONS OF WASTE SOLVENT WAS SPILLED. THE SAFETY-KLEEN WAREHOUSEMAN IMMEDIATELY APPLIED ABSORBENT MATERIAL TO THE AFFECTED AREA. ABSORBENT BOOMS WERE APPLIED TO CONTAIN THE SPILLAGE. ALL SPILLED MATERIAL, ABSORBENT MATERIAL AND CONTAMINATED GRAVEL PARTICLES WERE COLLECTED, DRUMMED, APPROPRIATELY LABELED, AND WAS SHIPPED TO SAFETY-KLEEN RECYCLING CENTER. FUTURE INCIDENTS CAN BE AVOIDED BY REPLACING WORN OUT HOSE GASKETS.

DUE TO THE FACT MANAGER STINE WAS OUT OF TOWN, A.D. MATY, CHIEF INSPECTOR FOR AAR BUREUA OF EXPLOSIVES, RESPONDED.  INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE FDI, 100 PSI FRANGIBLE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HAD BURST. DISC WAS REPLACED WITH LIKE KIND AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR CONTINUED TRANSPORTATION.  CAR WAS NOT EQUIPPED WITH BAFFLES OR SURGE DEVICES.  JOE DEBAM OF CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED OF THE INCIDENT.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: AT APPROXIMATELY 1630 HOURS MONDAY AUGUST 17, 1992, A CONRAIL BRAKEMAN REPORTED WHL PULLING TWO TANKCARS OUT OF THE CLASSIFICTION OIN BIG FOUR YARD, HE WAS SPLASHED WITH PRODUCT WHICH SPRAYED OUT THE TOP OF TANK CAR GATX 30166.  THE CONRAIL MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND FOUND A RUPTURED DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT HOUSING.  THE DISC WAS REPLACED BY THE MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT AND THE TANK CAR WAS FORWARDED TO DESTINATION AT 1745 HOURS 8/17/92. CONRAIL BRAKEMAN R.L. WILCOXIN WAS TAKEN TO THE HOSPITAL FOR TREATMENT OF CHEMICAL BURNS AND LOST SEVEN DAYS WORK.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Piping or Fittings
column168: WHILE CONDUCTING ROUTINE TANK CAR INSPECTIONS, SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIALS (SA/HM) F.H. LERCH NOTED PRODUCT DRIPPING FROM THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP ON NATX VALVE CAP APPROXIMATELY 1/2 TURN.  LEAK CONTINUED AND SA/HM LERCH LOOSENED THE BOTTOM OUTLET VALVE CAP AND WRAPPED GORTEX AROUND THE VALVE NOZZLE THREADS AND RETIGHTENED VALVE CAP WHICH STOPPED THE LEAK. CAR WAS TAGGED FOR REPAIR.  NO FURTHER EXCEPTIONS WERE NOTED. NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO TOM FLORES OF CHEMTREC, STEVE CAREY OF NEBRASKA STATE PATRO, AND JOEY MOUTON OF PHIBRO ENERGY.

column58: Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug); Manway or Dome Cover; Piping or Fittings
column168: APPROXIMATELY 9:40 A.M., A STRONG ODOR AND VAPORS WERE NOTICED COMING FROM CAR BY SWITCHING CREW IN MOSSVILLE YARD.  CAR WAS EMPTY WITH RESIDUE FROM LAST LOADED MOVEMENT.  REAGENT CHEMICAL, WESTLAKE, LOUISIANA WAS NOTIFIED AT 10:05 A.M. AND SENT RICKY BROUSSARD TO INSPECT CAR.  MR. BROUSSARD FOUND THE DOME LID LOOSE ALLOWING VAPORS (FUMES) TO ESCAPE THE DOME LID. THE DOME LID WAS SECURED BY MR. BROUSSARD AND CAR WAS OKAY TO MOVE AT 10:40 A.M.

column42: PETROLEUM GASES, LIQUEFIED OR LIQUEFIED PETROLEUM GAS
column168: CSX TRANSPORTATION YARD JOB Y-30320, SHOWING 14 CARS INTO E30 TRACK AT PHILADELPHIA DID NOT NOTICE THE SWITCH WAS LINED FOR SUN OIL'S INDUSTRY TRACK.  THE MOVEMENT ENTERED SUN OIL'S LOADING RACK TRACK AND STRUCK 5 TANK CARS THAT WERE BEING LOADED.  THE LOADING LINES BROKE LOOSE AT IMPACT AND PERMITTED THE RELEASE OF LP GAS.  THE AUTOMATIC SHUT OFF ON THE LOADING RACK ACTUATED AND STOPPED THE RELEASE.  SUN OIL PERSONNEL RESPONDED
